{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}} '''Etymological list of counties of Ireland''' is a list of the origins of the names of the [[Counties of Ireland|traditional counties of Ireland]], both north and south, including counties that are no longer used.
Unless otherwise stated, the origin of a name is from Irish.
==Counties== {| class="wikitable sortable" align="left" ! bgcolor="#EEEEEE" | County name ! class="unsortable" bgcolor="#EEEEEE" | Established ! bgcolor="#EEEEEE" | Province ! bgcolor="#EEEEEE" | Irish name ! class="unsortable" bgcolor="#EEEEEE" | Derivation |- align="left" | [[County Antrim|Antrim]] | c.1400 | [[Ulster]] | Aontroim | Named after the town of [[Antrim, County Antrim|Antrim]], which comes from ''Aontroim'', meaning "lone ridge". It was formerly spelt ''Aontruim''. An older alternative name was ''Aontreibh'' meaning "lone dwelling".<ref>http://www.logainm.ie/1411588.aspx</ref> The county was formed by merging a number of other counties in the Earldom of Ulster, notable [[Twescard]], from the Irish ''Tuaisceart'', "North" and Carrickfergus, from the Irish ''Carraig Fhearghais'', named after [[Fergus Mór mac Eirc]], the 6th-century king of [[Dál Riata]]. |- align="left" | [[County Armagh|Armagh]] | 1584/5 | [[Ulster]] | Ard Mhacha | Named after the town of [[Armagh]], which comes from ''Ard Mhacha'', meaning "[[Macha]]'s height". Macha was an Irish goddess associated with Ulster and Armagh, where she is said to have given birth to twins after racing a horse. |- align="left" | [[County Carlow|Carlow]] | 1306 | [[Leinster]] | Ceatharlach | Named after the town of [[Carlow]], which comes from ''Ceatharlach'', meaning "place of cattle". |- align="left" | [[County Cavan|Cavan]] | 1584 | [[Ulster]] | An Cabhán | Named after the town of [[Cavan]], which comes from ''An Cabhán'', meaning "the hollow". |- align="left" | [[County Clare|Clare]] | 1565 | [[Munster]] | An Clár | Possibly named after the town of [[Clarecastle]], which is made up of the Irish ''clár'' ("plain") and the English ''castle''. Alternatively, it may come from the [[Norman people|Norman]] [[de Clare]] family, who took their name in turn from the English town of [[Clare, Suffolk|Clare]], which probably gets its name from the Latin ''clarus'', "clear". Before 1565, the county was known as County [[Thomond]] (Irish ''Tuamhain'', from ''Tuadhmhumhain'', meaning "North Munster"). |- align="left" | [[County Cork|Cork]] | c. 1200 | [[Munster]] | Corcaigh | Named after the city of [[Cork (city)|Cork]], which comes from ''Corcach'', meaning "swamp". |- align="left" | [[County Donegal|Donegal]] | 1584/5 | [[Ulster]] | Dún na nGall | Named after the town of [[Donegal]], which comes from ''Dún na nGall'', meaning "stronghold of the foreigners" (i.e. the [[Viking]]s). An alternative name for the county is [[Tyrconnell|Tyrconnell or Tirconnell]], after a Gaelic territory of the same name. This comes from ''Tír Chonaill'', meaning "land of Conall" and is named after [[Conall Gulban]], a son of [[Niall of the Nine Hostages]], whose [[Northern Uí Néill|descendants]] founded the territory. Conall means "Strong Wolf" in Irish. |- align="left" | [[County Down|Down]] | early 16th century | [[Ulster]] | An Dún | The name is derived from ''Dún ná Lethglas'', the capital of the [[Dál Fiatach]], now modern day [[Downpatrick]].<ref name="DownII">Hughes and Hannan: ''Place-Names of Northern Ireland'', Volume Two, County Down II, The Ards, pg xx. The Queen's University of Belfast, 1992. {{ISBN|085389-450-7}}</ref> |- align="left" | [[County Dublin|Dublin]] | 1185 | [[Leinster]] | Áth Cliath/Duibhlinn | Named after the city of [[Dublin]], which comes from ''Duibhlinn'', meaning "black pool". ''Áth Cliath'' means "hurdled ford" and is the main Irish name for Dublin. |- align="left" | [[County Fermanagh|Fermanagh]] | 1584/5 | [[Ulster]] | Fear Manach | "Men of Manach". Manach may come from Old Irish ''Magh Eanagh'', "Country of the Lakes", making the whole derivation "Men (or Tribe) of the Country of the Lakes".<ref>https://theodora.com/encyclopedia/f/fermanagh.html</ref> |- align="left" | [[County Galway|Galway]] | 1565 | [[Connacht]] | Gaillimh | Named after the city of [[Galway]], which was named after the river Gaillimh (meaning "stoney"). The older name was ''Dún Bhun na Gaillimhe'', "stronghold at the mouth of the Gaillimh". |- align="left" | [[County Kerry|Kerry]] | c. 1200 | [[Munster]] | Ciarraí | "People of Ciar". From ''Ciar'' ("black" or "dark brown"), a personal name, and ''Raighe'' ("people" or "tribe"). The Ciar after whom Ciarrai is named was Ciar mac Fergus, son of [[Fergus mac Róich]], ex King of Ulster, and [[Medb|Queen Meabh of Connacht]], both major characters of the [[Ulster Cycle]]. |- align="left | [[County Kildare|Kildare]] | 1297 | [[Leinster]] | Cill Dara | Named after the town of [[Kildare]], which comes from ''Cill Dara'', meaning "church of the oak". |- align="left" | [[County Kilkenny|Kilkenny]] | c. 1200 | [[Leinster]] | Cill Chainnigh | Named after the town of [[Kilkenny]], which comes from ''Cill Chainnigh'', meaning "church of Cainnech". [[Cainnech of Aghaboe|Saint Cainnech]] allegedly converted the county to Christianity in 597. |- align="left" | [[County Laois|Laois]] | 1556 | [[Leinster]] | Laois | Named after the Gaelic territory of ''Uí Laoighis'', meaning "people of Lugaid Laígne". Lugaid was granted lands after driving out forces from Munster. His name derives from ''[[Lugh]]''. Laois was originally called Queen's County, after [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary]] ("Bloody Mary") who created the county in 1556. After the creation of the [[Irish Free State]], it was given its current name. |- align="left" | [[County Leitrim|Leitrim]] | 1565 | [[Connacht]] | Liatroim | Named after the town of [[Leitrim, County Leitrim|Leitrim]], which comes from ''liath'' ("grey") and ''droim'' ("ridge"). Originally spelt ''Liathdruim''. |- align="left" | [[County Limerick|Limerick]] | c. 1200 | [[Munster]] | Luimneach | Named after the city of [[Limerick]], whose Irish name possibly means "bare spot". The Vikings called it ''Hlymrekr'', which might be a transliteration of the Irish or could mean "mighty noise" from [[Old Norse]] ''hlym'' ("noise") and ''rekr'' ("mighty"). |- align="left" | [[County Londonderry|Derry]] | 1613/1585 | [[Ulster]] | Doire | "Oak wood". From ''Daire Coluimb Chille'', "The Oak-wood of Saint Columba". Columba comes from the Latin for "Dove". Previously ''Daire Calgaich'', "The Oak-wood of Calgach". Calgach may have been [[Calgacus]]. The name may come from [[Proto-Celtic]] ''*calg-ac-os,'' "Possessing a Blade" or "Possessing a Penis". The prefix "London" was added in 1613, after the town had been rebuilt across the river from its previous site, in recognition of donations from the livery companies of the City of London which had enabled the English and Scottish settlers to colonise the site. This was the same time as the County was formed. There is [[Derry/Londonderry name dispute|some dispute]] over whether to use the name Londonderry or Derry. Most of the area for County Londonderry came from the previous [[County Coleraine]], which was formed in 1585. Coleraine comes from ''Cúil Raithin'', "Nook of the Ferns". |- align="left" | [[County Longford|Longford]] | 1586 | [[Leinster]] | An Longfort | Named after the town of [[Longford]], which comes from ''An Longfort'', meaning "the [[inland port|port]]". The earlier spelling was ''An Longphoirt''. The term was invented by Irish chroniclers to describe a Viking ship enclosure or fortress. Longford was split off from county Westmeath in 1586. |- align="left" | [[County Louth|Louth]] | c. 1200 | [[Leinster]] | Lú | Named after the village of [[Louth, County Louth|Louth]], which was named after the Irish god ''[[Lugh]]'' (modern spelling ''Lú''). |- align="left" | [[County Mayo|Mayo]] | 1565 | [[Connacht]] | Maigh Eo | Named after the village of [[Mayo, County Mayo|Mayo]], which comes from ''Maigh Eo'', meaning "plain of the [[yew]]". |- align="left" | [[County Meath|Meath]] | 1297 | [[Leinster]] | An Mhí | "The middle". Meath was once one of the five provinces of Ireland, and the one in which the High King sat. It was formed into a county in 1297 but it was much bigger, encompassing the modern counties of Westmeath and Longford in addition to Meath. In 1547, it was reduced to its current size. |- align="left" | [[County Monaghan|Monaghan]] | 1585 | [[Ulster]] | Muineachán | Named after the town of [[Monaghan]], which comes from ''Muineachán''. "Muine" means "brake" (a thickly overgrown area) or "hillock", hence the county council's interpretation as "land of the little hills". It could also derive from "Muine Acháin", "Acháin" meaning "field", and so making "bushy field" or "hilly field". |- align="left" | [[County Offaly|Offaly]] | 1556 | [[Leinster]] | Uíbh Fhailí | Named after the Gaelic territory of [[Kingdom of Uí Failghe|Uí Failghe]], which existed from the 6th century until the death of its last king, Brian mac Cathaoir O Conchobhair Failghe, in 1556. After this, it was divided into Queen's County (modern day County Laois) and King's County (modern day County Offaly.) King's County was named after [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary's]] Consort, [[Philip II of Spain|Philip]]. The name was restored to Offaly after the creation of the [[Irish Free State]]. |- align="left" | [[County Roscommon|Roscommon]] | c. 1292 | [[Connacht]] | Ros Comáin | Named after the town of [[Roscommon]], which comes from ''Ros Comáin'', meaning "Comán's wood". It was named after [[Coman mac Faelchon|Saint Coman]], who founded the monastery of Roscommon around 550. |- align="left" | [[County Sligo|Sligo]] | 1565 | [[Connacht]] | Sligeach | Named after the town of [[Sligo]], which comes from ''Sligeach'', meaning "shelly place"; a reference to the large amounts of shellfish to be found in the river and its estuary. |- align="left" | [[County Tipperary|Tipperary]] | 13th century | [[Munster]] | Tiobraid Árann | Named after the town of [[Tipperary (town)|Tipperary]], which comes from ''Tiobraid Árann'', meaning "well of the Arra"; a reference to the river which flows through it. |- align="left" | [[County Tyrone|Tyrone]] | 1585 | [[Ulster]] | Tír Eoghain | Named after the Gaelic territory of ''Tír Eoghain'', meaning "Land of Eoghan". It was named after king [[Eógan mac Néill]], a son of king [[Niall of the Nine Hostages]]. Eógan founded the Kingdom of [[Ailech]], which eventually became Tyrone. |- align="left" | [[County Waterford|Waterford]] | c. 1200 | [[Munster]] | Port Láirge | Named after the city of [[Waterford]], which comes from [[Old Norse]] ''Veðrafjǫrðr'' ("[[Ovis|ram]] fjord"). The Irish name ''Port Láirge'' means "Larag's port" and was historically anglicised as ''Portlarga''. |- align="left" | [[County Westmeath|Westmeath]] | 1543 | [[Leinster]] | An Iarmhí | Named after the old province of Meath. ''An Iarmhí'' also means "West Meath" or, fully translated, "West Middle". |- align="left" | [[County Wexford|Wexford]] | 1200 | [[Leinster]] | Loch Garman | Named after the town of [[Wexford]], which comes from [[Old Norse]] ''Veisafjǫrðr'' ("fjord of the mud flats"). The Irish name ''Loch Garman'' means "Garman's lake/inlet" and is named after a legendary character called Garman Garbh, who was drowned in the mudflats at the mouth of the river Slaney by an enchantress, resulting in the lake that bears his name. ''Loch Garman'' was historically anglicised as ''Lochgarman'' or ''Loughgarman''. |- align="left" | [[County Wicklow|Wicklow]] | 1607 | [[Leinster]] | Cill Mhantáin | Named after the town of [[Wicklow]], which comes from [[Old Norse]] ''Víkingalág'' or ''Vikinga-ló'' ("meadow of the Vikings"). The Irish name ''Cill Mhantáin'' means "Church of Mantan" and is named after a contemporary of Saint Patrick who had his teeth knocked out by Irish pagans. Hence he was renamed Mantan, which means "toothless one" in Irish. ''Cill Mhantáin'' was historically anglicised as ''Kilmantan''. |- align="left" |}
