{{Infobox ethnic group |group = Palestinians in Egypt |image = |population = 270,245-300,000{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}} |popplace = [[Cairo]] ([[Greater Cairo]]) |languages = [[Arabic language|Arabic]] ([[Palestinian Arabic]]) |religions = [[Sunni Islam]] and [[Christianity]] |related =[[Palestinians]] }}
'''Palestinians in Egypt''' refers to the [[Palestinian refugee]]s who fled to Egypt during the [[1948 Palestine war]], and their descendants, as well as Palestinians expelled from Jordan, following the events of [[Black September in Jordan|Black September]]. Some Palestinians and their descendants have never been naturalized and so keep the distinct status of Palestinian refugee. Other Palestinians, mostly Christians,{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} received Egyptian citizenship through marriage with Egyptian nationals or by other means.
Furthermore, Palestinians refugees benefit from special rights granted by Egyptian Law. They can attend Egyptian public schools, access to healthcare, and have the same rights as Egyptian citizens except the right to vote.
There was also an earlier wave of Palestinian immigration, in which Palestinian Christians settled in Egypt during the [[Ottoman Syria|Ottoman era]], along with [[Lebanese people|Lebanese]] and [[Syrians]], forming what was known as the "[[Syro-Lebanese in Egypt|Shawam]]" (شوام) community.
Estimates of the size of the Palestinian population in Egypt range from 270,245 to 300,000{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}.
